\begin{minipage}[t]{0.50\linewidth}
\vspace{0pt}\small
\textbf{Unit costs.}
\begin{align*}
\headcost   &= 2 \seqlen \dhid \dhead = 2 \cdot 128 \cdot 768 \cdot 64 \\
            &= 12{,}582{,}912 \approx 12.58 \text{ M ops} \\[2pt]
\neuroncost &= 2 \seqlen \dhid = 2 \cdot 128 \cdot 768 \\
            &= 196{,}608 \approx 0.197 \text{ M ops}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Layer 0 ($\actl = 2$, $\nactl = 112$).}
\begin{align*}
\macop_0 &= 2 \cdot 12.58 + 112 \cdot 0.197 \\
         &\approx 25.2 + 22.0 \approx 47.2 \text{ M ops}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Candidate total.}
\[
\macop(\cand) = \sum_{\ell = 0}^{11} \macop_\ell \approx 249 \text{ M ops.}
\]

\textbf{Dense reference and keep ratio.}
\begin{align*}
\macdense   &= 12 (12 \cdot 12.58 + 3072 \cdot 0.197) \\
            &\approx 12 \cdot 756.1 \approx 9073 \text{ M ops} \\[2pt]
\keepratio(\cand) &= \macop(\cand) / \macdense \\
                  &\approx 249 / 9073 \approx 0.0274
\end{align*}

The candidate retains roughly $2.7\%$ of dense cost, with compute concentrated in the lower layers and the middle layers nearly emptied.
\end{minipage}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Feasibility Band}

The target budget $\budget$ is not generally reachable exactly. Head counts are integers and neuron counts are allocated in blocks of sixteen, so the set of attainable values of $\macop(\cand)$ is discrete and the chance that any single point coincides with $\budget$ is small. The search therefore accepts a candidate as feasible whenever its cost lies in a narrow band around the target,
\begin{equation}
(1 - \varepsilon) \budget \;\le\; \macop(\cand) \;\le\; (1 + \varepsilon) \budget ,
\label{eq:band}
\end{equation}
which keeps candidates at a comparable compute level and reduces the comparison between them to the question of where the budget is placed, not how much of it is spent. The half width $\varepsilon$ is a hyperparameter of the search, chosen small enough that the band does not confound compute reductions with metric improvements and large enough that repair operators have a non empty target set. Operation count is used for the constraint because it is deterministic and device independent; a deployment specific latency table can replace it without affecting the rest of the procedure.
